            <pb n="3" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>OPINION OF HUMBOLDT.</head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The opinion of Baron <hi rendition="#k">Humboldt</hi> upon &#x201C;mov-<lb break="no"/>ing tables&#x201D; is found in the Dresden Journal. Ac-<lb break="no"/>cording to a communication in that paper, <hi rendition="#k" >Hum-<lb break="no"/>boldt</hi> writes Dr. Franz Schlegel, M. D., of Alten-<lb break="no"/>burgh, in relation to two treatises upon &#x201C;moving ta-<lb break="no"/>bles&#x201D; by the Doctor. A friend has kindly given us a<lb break="yes"/>translation of the Baron&#x2019;s letter, which is as<lb break="yes"/>follows:</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;It is easier to combat a theory than facts imperfectly<lb break="yes" />observed. There are diseases of belief which return pe-<lb break="no" />riodically and are as endemical with the polished as with<lb break="yes"/>the lower classes, because in the former they assume the<lb break="yes"/>form of dogmatism and arrogance peculiar to the super-<lb break="no"/>ficial. I tender you, most honored Doctor, my kindest<lb break="yes"/>thanks for the publication of your very simple mechani-<lb break="no"/>cal explanation of the turning of tables towards the north<lb break="yes"/>pole. But you will convert nobody.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>With the highest esteem, &#x0026;c.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">ALEXANDER VON HUMBOLDT.</hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Berlin, April</hi> 18, 1853.</dateline>
            </div>
            <lb break="yes"/>
        </body>
